name: Microbiology Chapter 3 Quiz
description: Quiz questions for Chapter 3 of Microbiology covering cell theory, spontaneous generation, and cell structures.
subject: Microbiology

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: Who was earliest recorded scholar to articulate the theory of spontaneous generation?
questions.explanation: Aristotle was one of the earliest recorded scholars to articulate the theory of spontaneous generation.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: _____________   _____________ experimental setup consisted of an open container, a container sealed with a cork top, and a container covered in mesh that let in air but not flies.
questions.explanation: Francesco Redi’s experiment involved an open container, a sealed container, and a mesh-covered container to test spontaneous generation of maggots.
questions.imageAlt: Francesco Redi's experiment setup with three jars to disprove spontaneous generation of maggots from meat.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: Which of the following are anchored into the plasma membrane by a basal body composed of nine triplets of microtubules?
questions.explanation: Both eukaryotic flagella and eukaryotic cilia are anchored by a basal body with a 9+0 arrangement of microtubule triplets.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: The English scientist Robert Hooke first used the term “__________” in 1665 to describe the small chambers within cork that he observed under a microscope of his own design.
questions.explanation: Robert Hooke coined the term 'cells' after observing cork tissue.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: Who definitively refuted the long-disputed theory of spontaneous generation?
questions.explanation: Louis Pasteur's swan-neck flask experiments definitively refuted the theory of spontaneous generation.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: Which of the following is not part of the endomembrane system?
questions.explanation: Mitochondria are not part of the endomembrane system, which includes the ER, Golgi apparatus, lysosomes, and vesicles.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: In what decade did we recognize the modern cell theory?
questions.explanation: The modern cell theory was largely established by the 1850s through the work of Schleiden, Schwann, and Virchow/Remak.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: Eukaryotic cells possess a _____________, which is surrounded by a complex nuclear membrane that houses the ___________ .
questions.explanation: Eukaryotic cells have a nucleus that contains their DNA.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: Who was the first scientist to articulate the endosymbiotic hypothesis?
questions.explanation: Konstantin Mereschkowski was the first to articulate the endosymbiotic hypothesis in the early 20th century.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: Which of the following individuals did not contribute to the establishment of cell theory?
questions.explanation: Girolamo Fracastoro proposed early ideas about disease transmission but was not a direct contributor to cell theory. Schleiden, Hooke, and Remak (along with Schwann and Virchow) were key figures.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: In 1745, John Needham (1713–1781) published a report of his own experiments, in which he briefly boiled broth infused with plant or animal matter, hoping to kill all preexisting microbes.  He then sealed the flasks. After a few days, Needham observed that the broth had become cloudy and a single drop contained numerous microscopic creatures. He argued that the new microbes must have arisen spontaneously. What is the likely explanation for this result?
options: Needham likely did not boil the broth enough to kill all preexisting microbes.
All of the existing microbes had been killed
questions.explanation: Needham's boiling time was likely insufficient to kill heat-resistant endospores, leading to microbial growth.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: Which of the following terms refers to a prokaryotic cell that is spiral shaped?
questions.explanation: A spirillum is a spiral-shaped prokaryotic cell.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: _____________ is a form of transport used by bacteria, but not by eukaryotic cells, to move materials across the cell membrane and into the cell.
questions.explanation: Group translocation is a unique active transport mechanism in some bacteria where the substance is chemically modified during transport.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: Which bacterial structures are important for adherence to surfaces?
questions.explanation: Fimbriae are primarily involved in adherence, and flagella can also play a role in initial attachment for some bacteria.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: Who conducted studies to track the source of cholera outbreaks in London which ultimately resulted in the first known public health response to an epidemic?
questions.explanation: John Snow is considered the father of epidemiology for his work on the Broad Street cholera outbreak.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: _________________ cells lack a nucleus.
questions.explanation: Prokaryotic cells are defined by their lack of a membrane-bound nucleus.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: When the concentration of solutes is greater on one side of the membrane, water diffuses across the membrane from the side with the lower concentration (more water) to the side with the higher concentration (less water) until the concentrations on both sides become equal. This diffusion of water is called _____________ .
questions.explanation: Osmosis is the diffusion of water across a selectively permeable membrane from an area of high water concentration to an area of low water concentration.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: Mitochondria are unable to survive outside of eukaryotic cells. If they originated from ancestral prokaryotes, as proposed by the endosymbiotic theory, then why can’t they survive independently?
options: Over time, mitochondria and their host cells evolved to be dependent on each other.
Mitochondrial genes transferred to the cell nucleus.
The mitochondrion might not have all its genes therefore, it cannot perform all its functions if it is removed from the eukaryotic cell.
There should be no reason for the mitochondria to not survive independently.
questions.explanation: Mitochondria cannot survive independently due to co-evolution, transfer of essential genes to the host nucleus, and subsequent loss of genes for independent survival.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: Ribosomes are structures responsible for ________________ synthesis.
questions.explanation: Ribosomes are the sites of protein synthesis in both prokaryotic and eukaryotic cells.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: Which best describes the function of cristae?
options: They increase the surface area for reactions associated with cellular respiration.
They increase the capacity of the mitochondria to synthesize ATP
They provide a location for the light reactions of photosynthesis in plant cells.
They are compartments for digestive enzyme storage in eukaryotic cells.
questions.explanation: Cristae are folds in the inner mitochondrial membrane that increase surface area for ATP synthesis during cellular respiration.
